They did this through their Santa Fe Division, (Santa Fe California) and not only sporterizing the Schmidt Rubin 1911's but did Enfields, Mausers, Swiss K31s and a few others. This Swiss Model 1911 was converted to .308 caliber. The "".308"" is clearly marked on either the barrel or the side of the rear sight housing. The barrel was shortened to accommodate the re-chambering and the stock sporterized in a professional manner. These rifles are noted for their accuracy and they are!!!  This model was called the ""Alpine Sporter"".  This rifle was been drilled for a side scope mount and these holes were plugged.  I'm pretty sure this one has never had a scope on it.  This rifle is still in wonderful condition.  It will handle .308 factory loads without issue.  I've done a few things to this rifle myself:  I fitted with a very nice decelerator pad, the bolt was highly polished for super smooth operation and the last thing I did was to take the original trigger and have it modified to remove over 1/2"" of creep and the spring pressure reduced to give this trigger a very smooth and crisp 2.75lb pull.  I have a completely stock trigger assembly that will go with the rifle if you don't like a light trigger.  I shot it at targets so I liked a very light and crisp trigger.  If you've never shot a straight pull bolt rifle you're in for a treat.  The Swiss precision of this bolt is evident and you can cycle rounds in the blink of an eye.  This is also a great first starter hunting rifle.  I'm asking $300 for this rifle so it not so expensive that you have to worry about your young one hurting your expensive hunting rifle.  Call/Text Rick 5O5*6IO*529I"

987,http://www.armslist.com/posts/2936987,For Sale:  22LR Ammo!,"N CLT/Harrisburg/UNIV, Charlotte, North Carolina",$ 100,"Listed On: Tuesday, May 20, 2014",Ammo,no type,no type,no type,no type,"Thank you for viewing my listing, serious bidders only need apply.

Up for sale, I have a truly special piece of history—Norwegian heavy water fortified 22lr rounds, specially designed and manufactured by the Third Reich, in an attempt to be prepared for the inevitable dropping of an atomic bomb by Allied Forces upon German assets.  Upon dropping of an allied bomb, these rounds could be fired out of any 22lr, and reach a falling bomb at a maximum range of 2200 yards.  The plant these rounds were made in was a high profile target of SAS forces in 1942.

These rounds were too critical to the war effort to be stored in ammunition dumps or arsenals; rather, they were dispersed amongst trusted SS men, with instructions to carry them loose in the pockets—if discovered any other way, they would be shot on discovery of such improper ammunition storage.

If you look closely at the rounds, you can still see remnants of Flecktarn fibers, which indicate battlefield service.  Also, some rounds have been somewhat dislodged and the projectiles canted to a 15-20 degree angle, likely due to early war production rounds being subjected to excessive goose-stepping.

The brass is mainly clean, and has a German counterfeit mark, which makes the ammunition appear to be manufactured by Remington.  This was a clever move on the part of the Germans, as if capture occurred, POWs could hide the ammunition in the ground, or in their rectums upon thorough search.  If found, such ammunition would appear as commonplace, stolen, or found.  I have photocopies of Wehrmacht manuals which dictate these practices.
Some of the brass has a brown-spinach green tarnish on it, but I am sure that is from the age of the ammunition and the patina that comes even with storage in a climate controlled environment.

I have 40 of these rounds; the cash price would be $100.00 each, but I would consider trade values around 10 cents each.  Looking for ARs, Garands, or Colts if they are not too beat up.  Thanks, and take care.  No Lowballs."
